"# Chapter 3 — Chip families — TTL, DTL, CMOS

Chapter 2 was about gates as abstract Boolean things. This chapter
is about how those gates are actually built in silicon — and about
the different physical strategies engineers have used over the
decades. Different strategies had different tradeoffs: speed, power,
heat, cost, ease of manufacture. Some of these strategies were
dominant for a decade and then displaced. That's a common shape in
engineering.

## DTL — diode-transistor logic

Diode-transistor logic came first, in the early 1960s. It used diodes
to perform the logic and one transistor to amplify the output.
Diodes are simple, cheap, and slow. DTL chips were slow, but they
worked, and they were manufacturable in the state of the art at the
time.

DTL was dominant for a few years and then got replaced by TTL, which
was faster.

## TTL — transistor-transistor logic

Transistor-transistor logic replaced DTL in the mid-1960s. TTL used
multi-emitter transistors instead of diodes for the logic stage.
Faster switching, less power per gate, better fanout (a TTL gate
could drive more downstream inputs).

TTL dominated logic-chip design from about 1965 through the 1980s.
The most famous TTL family is the 74xx series, introduced by Texas
Instruments in 1966 and still available in updated forms decades
later. Every serious electronics hobbyist of a certain generation
has a shoebox of 7400 chips somewhere.

Some famous 74xx parts:
- **7400**: quad two-input NAND
- **7404**: hex inverter
- **7408**: quad two-input AND
- **7432**: quad two-input OR
- **7474**: dual D flip-flop (a memory cell — stores one bit)
- **7483**: 4-bit adder (chapter 2's ripple-adder, in one chip)
- **74181**: 4-bit ALU (arithmetic-logic unit — can add, subtract,
  AND, OR, XOR)

You could build a working 8-bit computer using only 74xx chips
soldered onto a board. People did. The Kenbak-1 (1971) — a
candidate for the title 'first personal computer' — was built from
TTL. Many home-computer projects since have been built the same way.

## CMOS — complementary metal-oxide semiconductor

By the late 1970s, engineers were figuring out that TTL had a
problem: it burned power all the time, whether the gate was switching
or not. TTL gates leak current continuously. That's fine for a few
gates on a board; it's terrible when you want to put a million gates
on one chip and run it from a battery.

CMOS solved this. A CMOS gate uses two complementary transistors — a
'PMOS' and an 'NMOS' — arranged so that one is always off. Current
only flows during the brief moment a gate is switching from one
state to the other. Static power consumption drops by orders of
magnitude.

CMOS was known theoretically from the mid-1960s but was hard to
manufacture reliably. Once the manufacturing caught up (mid to late
1970s), CMOS became the dominant technology for building integrated
circuits, and it has been ever since.

Every processor in your pocket is CMOS. Every RAM chip is CMOS.
Every SSD controller is CMOS. When people say 'the chip industry,'
they largely mean CMOS.

## Why the family matters

Different chip families have different signal levels, different
speeds, different power characteristics, different noise margins.
Chips from different families sometimes can't talk to each other
directly — you need a level-shifter or an interface chip.

This is more than a technicality. When you're wiring an old computer
into a modern breadboard project, or building a level converter for
5-volt legacy hardware talking to 3.3-volt modern hardware, this is
the topic you're working on.

Motoi is not going to help you level-shift 5V to 3.3V. But knowing
the family is why the levels are different is honest computer
literacy.

## Standard cells

Modern chip design doesn't have engineers laying out individual
transistors for every gate. Instead, foundries publish libraries of
'standard cells' — pre-designed layouts for each kind of gate, at
several drive strengths. A chip designer's tool places cells and
routes wires between them. The cells are the modern equivalent of
the 74xx chips: reusable building blocks at the size and abstraction
appropriate to the era.

The abstraction stack:
- Chip designer works with standard cells.
- Cells are built from transistors.
- Transistors are built from silicon crystal structure.
- The crystal is grown, sliced, etched, and doped in a fab.
- Photolithography is used to pattern the layers.

Every layer of that stack takes a lifetime to master. The whole
industry runs because different specialists work at different levels
and trust each other's abstractions.

## A tiny example

Simulating a couple of gate families with different signal levels in
Motoi Scheme, just to show the shape:

```
(define ttl-high 5.0)   ;; volts
(define ttl-low  0.0)

(define cmos-high 3.3)
(define cmos-low  0.0)

(define (interpret-ttl v)
  (cond ((>= v 2.0) #t)
        ((<= v 0.8) #f)
        (else 'indeterminate)))

(define (interpret-cmos v)
  (cond ((>= v 2.5) #t)
        ((<= v 0.8) #f)
        (else 'indeterminate)))

(interpret-ttl 5.0)   ;; => #t
(interpret-ttl 3.3)   ;; => #t   (CMOS output looks HIGH to TTL, usually ok)
(interpret-cmos 5.0)  ;; => #t   (but pushing 5V into CMOS input can damage it!)
(interpret-cmos 2.0)  ;; => indeterminate
```

Those threshold voltages are why you can't just wire everything
together. Motoi doesn't do this level of engineering, but knowing the
shape helps make sense of retro-computing projects and hardware
histories.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Different eras used different physical strategies to build the same
logical gates. TTL was fast for its time. CMOS is efficient. Both
are arrangements of transistors implementing Boolean logic. The
logic doesn't care which family you use. But the electrical behavior
sure does.

This is also why old computers have such distinct personalities.
The C64 uses NMOS logic families that run hot. The Amiga uses
faster NMOS custom chips plus CMOS controllers. Each machine feels
different partly because the underlying physics is different.")
